{{Infobox book | italic title = <!--(see above)--> | name = Geometry and the Imagination | image = Geometry and the Imagination.jpg| image_size = | alt = | caption = | author = | audio_read_by = | title_orig = Anschauliche Geometrie | orig_lang_code = | title_working = | translator = Paul Nemenyi | illustrator = | cover_artist = | country = | language = | series = | release_number = | subject = | genre = | set_in = | publisher = [[American Mathematical Society]] | publisher2 = | pub_date = 1959 | english_pub_date = | published = | media_type = | pages = 357 | awards = | isbn = 9780821819982 | isbn_note = | oclc = 542459 | dewey = | congress = | preceded_by = | followed_by = | native_wikisource = | wikisource = | notes = | exclude_cover = | website = }}
'''''Geometry and the Imagination''''' ({{lang-de|Anschauliche Geometrie}}) is a book by [[David Hilbert]] and [[Stephan Cohn-Vossen]]<ref>{{Cite book|title=Geometry and the imagination|last1=Hilbert|first1=David|author-link1=David Hilbert|last2=Cohn-Vossen|first2=Stephan|author-link2=Stephan Cohn-Vossen|date=1999|publisher=AMS Chelsea Pub|isbn=9780821819982|edition=2nd|location=Providence, R.I.|oclc=41256151}}</ref> based on a series of lectures Hilbert made in the winter of 1920–21. The book is an attempt to present some then-current mathematical thought to "contribute to a more just appreciation of mathematics by a wider range of people than just the specialists."<ref>Hilbert, page iv</ref>
== Response == The [[Mathematical Association of America]] said about the book, "this book is a masterpiece — a delightful classic that should never go out of print".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.maa.org/press/maa-reviews/geometry-and-the-imagination|title=Geometry and the Imagination {{!}} Mathematical Association of America|website=www.maa.org|access-date=2017-10-01}}</ref> [[Physics Today]] called it "a readable exposition of modern geometry and its relation to other branches of mathematics".<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Hilbert|first=D.|last2=Cohn‐Vossen|first2=S.|date=May 1953|title=Geometry and the Imagination|url=http://physicstoday.scitation.org/doi/10.1063/1.3061234|journal=Physics Today|language=en|doi=10.1063/1.3061234}}</ref> [[The Scientific Monthly]] said about it "has been a classic for twenty years . . . Although it deals with elementary topics, it reaches the fringe of our knowledge in many directions".<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Coxeter|first=H.S.M.|date=February 1953|title=Review: Intuitive Geometry|jstor=20643|journal=The Scientific Monthly|volume=76| issue = 2|pages=117–118}}</ref>
